WITH this exact block:
double penalty = 0.0;

// NO type selection here; penalty_fn_* already fixed at parse/init time.
if (cfg_.overlap_c.enabled)
    penalty += cfg_.overlap_c.weight * overlap_penalty_fn_(overlap_pen);

if (cfg_.boundary_c.enabled)
    penalty += cfg_.boundary_c.weight * boundary_penalty_fn_(boundary_agg);

if (cfg_.aspect_c.enabled)
    penalty += cfg_.aspect_c.weight * aspect_penalty_fn_(aspect_vi);


✅ Result:

simple_penalty behaves exactly like before (square).

barrier types add exp/log penalties with no runtime decision overhead.

CHANGE 7 — Fix a critical HPWL bug in your loop (REPLACE 2 lines)

In your loop inside compute_all() you have:

max_cx = std::min(max_cx, cx);
max_cy = std::min(max_cy, cy);


That is wrong (max should use std::max), and it will completely break HPWL.

REPLACE those 2 lines with:
max_cx = std::max(max_cx, cx);
max_cy = std::max(max_cy, cy);

Notes on “barrier” definitions

Because your config does not provide extra parameters (like barrier scale, epsilon, feasible margin), the above uses fast, safe defaults:

barrier_penalty-exp: expm1(v)

barrier_penalty-log: log1p(v)

Both are:

monotonic increasing for v ≥ 0

exactly 0 at v = 0

cheap (only 3 calls per iteration max)

If you later want per-constraint tuning (e.g., barrier_scale), we can add a double barrier_scale; to ConstraintConfig and still avoid branches in compute_all() (but we’d need a different mechanism than a plain function pointer—still doable fast).

Also fix your config key mismatch (important)

Your config uses:

"stopping_criteria": "maxiter"


but your callback checks:

if(stopping_mode_ == "target_objective")


So "maxiter" is fine, but make sure you are consistent elsewhere (some earlier code used "max_iter").
